  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a real, tangible barrier that affects how people perform, especially when they're from groups that have been historically marginalized in these fields. As a woman who's worked with my hands in construction for over twenty years, I've seen firsthand how fear of being judged or labeled can hold people back. My own anxiety about being seen as 'not smart enough' in math or science classes during my lower secondary education still lingers, even though I've since built a solid career in carpentry. Stereotype threat isn't just about the fear of failure; it's the mental load of constantly proving yourself against a narrative that says you don't belong. I believe we absolutely must address this issue because it's not just a matter of fairness—it's a practical necessity for innovation. When people are anxious about their place in a field, they don't focus on solving problems; they focus on avoiding embarrassment. In Chicago, where we have a diverse population, this issue is particularly acute for women and people of color who might feel they don't fit the 'typical' STEM persona. The solution isn't about changing the stereotypes themselves but about creating environments where everyone feels safe to make mistakes and learn. This means teachers and mentors who actively challenge the idea that only certain types of people can excel in STEM, and workplaces that value diverse perspectives. I've seen this work in my community through local workshops where we focus on practical, hands-on projects rather than abstract theory. If we can create spaces where people feel they belong, rather than afraid to participate, we'll see more diverse talent in STEM fields—because everyone deserves to have their full potential realized.",
